{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619730"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:35:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:35:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16573"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16573"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.58,0.05,0.16,0.16,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9264"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75723"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9264"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16573"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61241"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2443"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10346"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21946"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21951"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75723"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe skull is a rigid structure containing brain tissue, cerebrospinal fluid (CSF), and blood vessels. According to the Monro-Kellie doctrine, the total volume within the skull must remain constant.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the initial compensatory response to raised intracranial pressure?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased CSF absorption with reduced CSF volume","Increased CSF production with reduced blood volume","Reduced CSF absorption with decreased blood volume","Reduced blood volume with increased CSF volume","Reduced brain tissue volume with increased CSF volume"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the Monro-Kellie doctrine, when intracranial pressure rises, the brain initiates compensatory mechanisms. \u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased CSF absorption with reduced CSF volume\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary response, allowing space for the expanding mass or increased pressure while maintaining vital brain function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect responses can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased CSF production with reduced blood volume\u003C/strong\u003E - Increasing CSF production would worsen the pressure problem\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced CSF absorption with decreased blood volume\u003C/strong\u003E - Reduced absorption would prevent the necessary decrease in CSF volume\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced blood volume with increased CSF volume\u003C/strong\u003E - While blood volume may decrease as a later compensatory mechanism, increasing CSF volume would be counterproductive\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced brain tissue volume with increased CSF volume\u003C/strong\u003E - Brain tissue volume cannot be readily reduced, and increasing CSF volume would worsen the pressure\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis compensatory mechanism has limits - once exhausted, intracranial pressure will rise rapidly, potentially leading to brain herniation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The Monro-Kellie doctrine states that the sum of brain tissue, CSF, and blood volume within the cranium must remain constant.","In response to raised intracranial pressure, CSF absorption increases and CSF volume decreases to maintain homeostasis.","This compensatory mechanism helps protect the brain from damage due to raised pressure."],"references":["Canac N, Jalaleddini K, Thorpe SG, Thibeault CM, Hamilton RB. Review: pathophysiology of intracranial hypertension and noninvasive intracranial pressure monitoring. Fluids Barriers CNS. 2020 Jun 23;17(1):40. doi: 10.1186/s12987-020-00201-8. PMID: 32576216; PMCID: PMC7310456.","Pinto VL, Tadi P, Adeyinka A. Increased Intracranial Pressure. 2023 Jul 31. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29489250.","Tripathy S, Ahmad SR. Raised Intracranial Pressure Syndrome: A Stepwise Approach. Indian J Crit Care Med. 2019 Jun;23(Suppl 2):S129-S135. doi: 10.5005/jp-journals-10071-23190. PMID: 31485121; PMCID: PMC6707500.","Tasker RC. Raised intracranial pressure during CNS infection: what should we do about it?*. Crit Care Med. 2014 Aug;42(8):1936-8. doi: 10.1097/CCM.0000000000000419. PMID: 25029130; PMCID: PMC4151569."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61241"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16573"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61241"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T20:29:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T20:31:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9264"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75723"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":